## **High level diagram** {#high-level-diagram}

A user enters a task in the Streamlit UI chat input, the Clarification agent asks questions tailored to the task, and after the human provides the input again(i.e. once clarified), the Planner agent builds an outline, and the Researcher agent then fetches sources relevant for the task(dynamic behaviour). Then the Writer agent drafts the report, and the Critic agent reviews this draft and asks for revisions, which the research\_critique uses to find new sources and the cycle repeats until the max revision limit is reached, then a PDF is generated which can be downloaded.  
**![][image1]**

## **Architecture** {#architecture}

### **Frontend(streamlit)** {#frontend(streamlit)}

To keep track of message history I have used st.session\_state.history. Apart from the history I have also used st.session\_state to keep track of other things like, clar\_q, thread, revision\_number, etc.

    	![][image2]  
The last *for loop* prints all the messages from the chat history(st.session\_state.histroy) whenever the streamlit reruns everything. (whenever there is any user input streamlit reruns everything so session\_state is a way to make data persist for the frontend). 

![][image3]  
The above code is for the clarification question, we enter the if block if *st.session\_state\_has\_clar\_q* is set to False(initially it is False). The llm generates appropriate clarification questions based on the task(refer to section: *Langgraph Specifics*). This is printed to the chat container(using st.chat\_message). Then we just step through the graph nodes and **interrupt after the clarification\_node** node and make updates to the session\_state(to achieve human in the loop behaviour for getting clarifications from the user). Now that we have the clarification\_question we can ask the user for clarification. For that we do st.rerun().

![][image4]  
Here we enter the elif code block on the next run(as st.rerun was called in the previous block and as has\_clar\_q is set to True). We then ask the user for input through the chat input and append it to the message history and also print it to the chat container. We then step through the  nodes and based on specific nodes run some specific actions(like adding them to the history and printing them to the chat container).  
![][image5]  
The generate step is important, we keep track of the revision number and when it reaches 3 i.e. after 1 revision we generate a pdf. (hardcoded it here just for simplicity)  
![][image6]  
The above code is just printing the markdown to the UI in the chat container and also updating the history, at the end we set has\_clar\_q to False.

### **LangGraph Specifics** {#langgraph-specifics}

**![][image7]**  
For ensuring that the llm has knowledge about previous conversations, I am using InMemorySaver(). (Note: The persistence using st.session\_state was for the frontend as the UI will be rendered multiple times based on user input, this is for the llm itself).

![][image8]  
I have defined the Agent state with various attributes that I want to be able to access from any node. Its use is demonstrated further below.

![][image9]Using the gemini 2.5 flash model for a higher context window(1 million tokens) and setting the temperature to 0 to have deterministic output(as the most probable next token is chosen every time instead of being sampled).

![][image10]  
![][image11]  
System message is the CLARIFICATION\_PROMPT which was designed by providing a rough outline to gpt-4o which refined it(same is the case for all other SYSTEM\_PROMPTS).

Human message is the actual task input by the user.

The function takes these 2 things and outputs clarification\_questions, which is then overwritten in the state.  
(state which is of type AgentState is passed around, so any node can access this now).

![][image12]  
![][image13]  
Plan prompt is given the clarification\_question and the clarification provided by the user in the system prompt. Human message includes the task which was input by the user previously and was stored in the task attribute of state.  
The plan attribute in the state is overwritten(output).

![][image14]  
![][image15]  
![][image16]

Research\_plan node basically collects the sources from the web using Agentic search using Tavily. (this is more powerful than manual web scraping as the output is structured i.e. json by default so we don't have to write manual string manipulation code). For each of the queries it generates 2 results and adds that to the content attribute of the state.  
![][image17]  
**Note**: 	queries \= model.with\_structured\_output(Queries).invoke(\[  
    	SystemMessage(content=RESEARCH\_PLAN\_PROMPT.format(  
            	plan=state\['plan'\])),  
    	HumanMessage(content=state\['task'\])\])  
The system prompt is to generate some number of queries and using **model.with\_structured\_output** makes sure the output is returned as a Queries object.  
So now *queries* is a Queries object, and *queries.queries* is the list of search-query strings.

Generation\_node uses the plan and the content to generate a draft and also updates the revision\_number. If critique and draft is available from the previous iteration it also uses that to refine that draft further.

![][image18]  
![][image19]  
![][image20]  
Refelection\_node: Takes the draft as the input and overwrites the critique attribute in the state.  
Research\_critique\_node: Takes the critique as input and uses agentic search using tavility based on the queries that were generated by the llm. Each query gives 2 results max and is appended to the content attribute.

![][image17]  
**Note**: 	queries \= model.with\_structured\_output(Queries).invoke(\[  
    	SystemMessage(content=RESEARCH\_CRITIQUE\_PROMPT),  
    	HumanMessage(content=state\['critique'\])\])  
The system prompt is to generate some number of queries and using **model.with\_structured\_output** makes sure the o	utput is returned as a Queries object.  
So now queries is a Queries object, and queries.queries is the list of search-query strings.

![][image21]  
Builder is a StateGraph which is a LangGraph Class to create a graph using some nodes and edges, to design the flow of information in essence.  
I have also used a conditional edge between generate and the reflect node/END. So while the number of revisions is less than equals max revision we continue reflecting, collecting new resources and generating but otherwise we END the loop and provide the final draft and the pdf download button(as defined above).
